---
import CalculatorLayout from "../../layouts/CalculatorLayout.astro";
import { AwsEbsSnapshotCostCalculator as AwsEbsSnapshotCostCalculatorComponent } from "../../components/calculators/AwsEbsSnapshotCost";

const title = "AWS EBS Snapshot Cost Calculator";
const description =
  "Estimate AWS EBS snapshot storage cost from changed-block growth, retention windows, and per-GB-month pricing, with scenario planning for backup churn and short-lived spikes.";
---
<CalculatorLayout
  title={title}
  description={description}
  canonicalPath="/calculators/aws-ebs-snapshot-cost-calculator"
  intro="Estimate EBS snapshot storage cost using a simplified steady-state model: full volume + daily changed data retained over the retention window. Compare baseline vs peak churn."
  examples={[
    "1,000 GB volume, 2% daily changes, 30-day retention -> estimate stored GB and monthly cost.",
    "Peak 220% scenario highlights backfill or batch churn."
  ]}
  includes={[
    "Snapshot stored volume estimate (steady state) from volume + change rate + retention.",
    "Monthly snapshot storage cost estimate from stored GB and $/GB-month.",
    "Optional daily change GB estimator.",
    "Baseline vs peak scenario table for change spikes.",
  ]}
  excludes={[
    "Provider-specific snapshot optimizations, rounding rules, and compression behavior.",
    "Data transfer, requests, and restore fees if applicable.",
  ]}
  how={[
    "Daily changed GB = volume GB x daily change rate.",
    "Estimated stored GB ~ volume GB + daily changed GB x (retention days - 1).",
    "Monthly cost ~ stored GB x $/GB-month.",
  ]}
  faqs={[
    {
      q: "Is this exact?",
      a: "No. Snapshot storage is incremental and depends on real change patterns. This is a planning estimate to avoid under-budgeting.",
    },
    {
      q: "What daily change rate should I use?",
      a: "Start with measured churn (writes) if you have it. If unsure, model scenarios (1%, 2%, 5%, 10%) and validate later.",
    },
    {
      q: "What else should I model for EBS?",
      a: "EBS volume storage plus performance add-ons (IOPS/throughput on some types), plus snapshot storage and retention policy.",
    },
  ]}
  lastUpdated="2026-01-29"
  related={[
    { href: "/guides/aws-ebs-snapshot-cost", label: "Guide: EBS snapshot cost" },
    { href: "/guides/aws-ebs-pricing", label: "Guide: EBS pricing" },
    { href: "/calculators/aws-ebs-cost-calculator", label: "EBS cost calculator" },
    { href: "/calculators/database-storage-growth-cost-calculator", label: "Database storage growth" },
  ]}
>
  <AwsEbsSnapshotCostCalculatorComponent client:load />
  <div class="prose" style="margin-top:18px">
    <h2 style="margin-top:0">EBS snapshot cost is mostly a changed-data and retention problem</h2>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:8px">
      Snapshot bills become misleading when teams think in full volumes instead of changed blocks. The important drivers
      are how much data changes each day, how long those changes are retained, and whether one-off rebuilds create
      temporary churn spikes that look nothing like an ordinary week.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Volume baseline</strong>: the protected dataset that anchors the first snapshot layer.</li>
      <li><strong>Daily churn</strong>: the real multiplier that turns routine backups into accumulating stored data.</li>
      <li><strong>Retention</strong>: the policy choice that decides how long changed data keeps stacking up.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Where snapshot estimates usually drift</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Daily change rate is guessed too low because only calm periods are measured.</li>
      <li>One-off rebuilds, reindexing, patching, or migration work create far more changed blocks than the baseline model assumed.</li>
      <li>Retention grows quietly over time, so the estimate keeps using last quarter's policy while the real window gets longer.</li>
      <li>Teams talk about total volume size when the snapshot bill is really being pushed by changed-data accumulation.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>What to review before trusting the snapshot baseline</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Measure ordinary daily churn separately from rebuild or maintenance windows.</li>
      <li>Review retention policy and cleanup habits because they control how long changed blocks remain billable.</li>
      <li>Model peak churn months explicitly instead of hiding them inside one blended average.</li>
      <li>Keep snapshot storage separate from volume storage so the two bills do not get mixed together.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Baseline vs churn-spike snapshot scenarios</h2>
    <table>
      <thead>
        <tr>
          <th>Scenario</th>
          <th>Daily change</th>
          <th>Retention</th>
          <th>Stored GB</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr>
          <td>Baseline</td>
          <td>Typical</td>
          <td>Standard</td>
          <td>Estimated</td>
        </tr>
        <tr>
          <td>Peak</td>
          <td>High</td>
          <td>Same</td>
          <td>Higher</td>
        </tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <h2>How to review the first real snapshot month</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Check whether the miss came from daily churn, retention length, or one-off maintenance events before changing the whole model.</li>
      <li>Compare actual stored snapshot GB to the retention window you thought was active, not just to raw volume size.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Next steps</h2>
    <div class="btn-row" style="margin-top:0">
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/">Guides</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/">All calculators</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-ebs-snapshot-cost/">Guide: EBS snapshot cost</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/guides/aws-ebs-pricing/">Guide: EBS pricing</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/aws-ebs-cost-calculator/">EBS cost calculator</a>
      <a class="btn" href="/calculators/database-storage-growth-cost-calculator/">Database storage growth</a>
    </div>
    <p class="muted" style="margin-top:12px">
      Use this calculator as a retained snapshot-growth model, then confirm daily churn, retention policy, copy
      behavior, and one-off maintenance spikes before you sign off on the snapshot budget.
    </p>
  </div>
</CalculatorLayout>


